I love this place. Their food is fantastic, offering both American-style Chinese food and homestyle Chinese. The service, however, is my favorite part of the experience. The staff treat you like family. They're incredibly friendly, and greet you on entry every time. When I say I want takeout, I'm ushered to a table by who I believe to be the owner, handed and menu with a smile, and told to take my time. Once, I forgot that they only do card transactions over $15, and they took my card anyway! I said I would be willing to add more to the order, and the nice woman said that she doesn't want me to order something I don't need. The atmosphere is like you're eating at home, which is a nice feeling. The prices are also very reasonable! This place is simply amazing, and I love coming here.

This is a restaurant that I last visited about thirty years ago.  At the time, I thought it was mediocre at best, worse than every other Chinese restaurant I had ever been to.  And Asian food is my favorite food so that was very disappointing.  Upon seeing it again recently, I stopped in again for lunch.  After thirty years, they must have had many generations of chefs come and go.  Perhaps management has changed and maybe multiple times.  I eagerly looked forward to yet another great Chinese meal.  Again, mediocre.  Again, very disappointing.  I don't know what the problem is but, having tried several BU area restaurants, I'll just recommend leaving the BU area.  All the restaurants have been bad...and expensive as well.

Beijing Cafe is one of those rare restaurants that, despite all its flaws,  keeps drawing me back. The food varies from fantastic to near-inedible depending on the day, time, and perhaps alignment of the stars, the staff is often seemingly absent, and its in a basement along a busy street that often feels damp during the winter months. Yet its always quiet and surprisingly clean, the service is always quick, the food is cheap, and it is incredibly convenient for BU students or visitors. Years after we've all left the area, my friends and I still come back to this place to catch up. Maybe its Stockholm syndrome, but I can't help but love this place.
